                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2008/11/eat-it&amp;text=Eat it" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Eat%20it%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2008%2F11%2Feat-it" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>All rise for the Honorable Chairman.</p>
<p>Hi y'all. Isn't it just a beautiful day in Durham?</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>I guess. Although it's a little too cold for the Chairman's liking... considering I make my permanent home in Quito, Ecuador. &iquest;Qu&eacute; pasa, mi bretheren internacional?</p>
<p>Well, at least it's nice enough to spend a leisurely Monday out on the Plaza.</p>
<p>Ahhhh, that was fun... for about five minutes.</p>
<p>Oh man, do I love the Plaza. There's excitement at every turn. There's the Loop. There's Subway. There's the Great Hall. There's Panda Express. There's Pauly Dogs. There's... hold on a second... I think I'm gonna hurl...</p>
<p>Perhaps some of you have heard of a little competition called the Hillsborough 500? For those of you who aren't "in the know," it is a challenge during which one tours the entirety of Hillsborough Rd., up and down, stopping to eat at every food place along the way. Sound difficult? Well, it is. I can never get past Waffle House.</p>
<p>The reason I bring up this time-honored tradition for masticating, masochistic Dukies is to christen my new event: The Plaza 500.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Same premise, except with the Plaza functioning as Hillsborough Rd. Think you can do it? Fat chance (literally).</p>
<p>You see, the Plaza is great... for eating.</p>
<p>On the occasion of the Plaza's opening in 2006, optimism filled the air. Chris Roby, then director of Student Life, even went so far as to say, "The opportunities are endless."</p>
<p>Really? Cool. I guess that means a Bojangles' soon.</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
                    <input type="hidden" value="1" name="group[29][1]" id="mce-group[29]-29-0">

                    <div class="input-group-append">
                        <input type="submit" value="Subscribe" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm sends-events" data-ga-category="CTA" data-ga-action="email_focus" data-ga-label="c4087a59c7" />
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div style="position: absolute; left: -5000px;"><input type="text" name="b_c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b_c4087a59c7" tabindex="-1" value=""></div>

            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Now I don't mean to criticize the Plaza. I really do think it's a great place to hang out and table. In addition to places to purchase food it has places to eat said food. And it has places to sit. And all this for the bargain price of...</p>
<p>$10 million.</p>
<p>Yikes. Sounds like a Dr. Evil figure to me.</p>
<p>But the Plaza is endemic of a greater Duke issue: Campus Culture. Now, lest you think these buzzwords are dead and gone since the now famous (or infamous) Campus Culture Initiative made its recommendations, I am here to revive them in a different light. At the height of the Initiative (which I guess is ongoing... I guess), one major topic dominated all talk of Duke's Campus Culture: alcohol. Although alcohol is prevalent on Duke's campus, it is just a distraction from the main issue.</p>
<p>You see, Duke's campus culture isn't focused on drinking, it's focused on eating.</p>
<p>Don't believe me? Look around. Take the Bryan Center, for instance. For food, it contains Alpine Atrium, the Armadillo Grill, the Lobby Shop and McDonald's. For student activities, it contains... a movie theater and a pool table.</p>
<p>What gives?</p>
<p>Although some fratstars would disagree, the prevailing notion is that, unlike alcohol, humans need food to survive. But food is all too abundant on Duke's campus. It encourages people to eat, go to class, sleep and eat some more. And, unlike at parties with alcohol, students are pretty unlikely to meet new people over food.</p>

                                                    <div class="related my-4 py-4 d-print-none">
                                <h3 class="kicker mb-4">Read more</h3>

                                                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed mb-4">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/letter-to-the-editor-duke-university-in-memoriam-wilhelmina-reuben-cooke-racial-justice-equity-hero">Letter: In memoriam: Wilhelmina Reuben-Cooke, Duke hero</a></h3>
                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed mb-4">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/duke-palantir-is-welcome-here">Palantir is welcome here</a></h3>
                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/the-tragedy-of-the-toilets-lifestyle">The tragedy of the toilets</a></h3>
                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>Hey.</p>
<p>Hey. How's your Loop 'n Cheddar?</p>
<p>Ummmm. overcooked.</p>
<p>Oh. Cool!</p>
<p>Now let's try that interaction in a setting with alcohol.</p>
<p>Hey dude.</p>
<p>Hey brah. How's that punch?</p>
<p>Sick.</p>
<p>Sick. Wanna shotgun?</p>
<p>Ahhh... I can already see the chemistry.</p>
<p>Now, the Chairman does not condone drinking alcohol in the least, and especially to excess. Heck, I have two sons and a daughter to look out for. But I do think that the University should do more to address the food saturation around campus. After all, isn't food poisoning just as prevalent as alcohol poisoning?</p>
<p>Instead of realizing food's foothold on Campus Culture, the CCI actually recommended more food on campus. Although not in so many words, the 2007 CCI report made note of the need for sit-down restaurants to lessen the influence of so-called "food courts." Now, if the University realized the dangers that all this food poses to an increasingly sedentary student body, they might begin to speak of it in the same breath as alcohol. I might be way off here, but I don't think the report would make a recommendation for communal keg stations on campus simply because they bring people together.</p>
<p>So, Duke, now that you've spent $10 million on a glorified patio, please, use it as a starting point to fight the insidious influence of food on this campus. Bring back that big chess set. Bring in entertainment carts with puppet shows and magic instead of more food carts. Heck, even bring back Tattoo... he (she?) added a certain something.</p>
<p>And this onus shouldn't fall solely on the shoulders of the administration. Take some initiative, students! Instead of hawking your cheap wares at flimsy OSAF tables, stage Plaza sit-ins until someone comes to your next a cappella show. That'll show 'em... and provide great entertainment for passers-by.</p>
<p>Now, to conclude, since the University so easily dropped 10 milli on the Plaza, I present a list of student activities that can be had for under 10,000,000 dollars.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>iPods</p></li>
<li><p>Working e-Prints</p></li>
<li><p>The 2012 Summer Olympics</p></li>
<li><p>Lupe Fiasco</p></li>
</ol>
<p>And that's just the beginning. The opportunities are endless.</p>
<p>Meeting Adjourned.</p>
<p>THE CHAIRMAN thinks the Great Hall would make a killer laser tag arena. Just throwing that out there.</p>
                                    </div>

